{{Infobox Book | name = My Traitor's Heart: A South African Exile Returns to Face His Country, His Tribe and His Conscience | title_orig = | translator = | image = | image_caption = | author = Rian Malan | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = South Africa | language = English | series = | subject = | genre = Autobiography, Politics | publisher = Atlantic Monthly Press | pub_date = 1990 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 349 | isbn = 0-87113-229-X | dewey= 968/.00992 B 20 | congress= CT1929.M35 A3 1990 | oclc= 20016093 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''My Traitor's Heart''''' is an [[autobiography|autobiographical]] book by [[Rian Malan]] first published in 1990 on his return from exile.<ref name=Traitor>{{Citation| last = Malan | first = Rian| title = My traitor's heart: A South African exile returns to face his country, his tribe and his conscience | publisher = Grove Press| date = | location = New York| id = | isbn = 0-8021-3684-2}}</ref> It is subtitled '''''South African Exile Returns to Face His Country, His Tribe and His Conscience''''' or ''Blood and Bad Dreams: A South African Exile Explores the Madness in His Country, His Tribe and Himself''.
The book describes Malan's experience of growing up in [[Apartheid]]-era South Africa in which he explores race relations through prominent murder cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/01/19/books/books-of-the-times-the-harsh-judgments-of-a-white-south-african.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=Books of The Times; The Harsh Judgments of a White South African|author=William Finnegan|work=New York Times|date=19 January 1990}}</ref><ref name=Adams>{{Citation| last = Adams| first = Tim| title = The dark heart of the new South Africa| newspaper = [[The Observer]]| date = 2007-03-25| url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/mar/25/southafrica.society| accessdate = 2009-09-05}}</ref> In addition, he reflects on the history of his family, a prominent Afrikaner clan that migrated to the Cape in the 17th century and included [[Daniel François Malan]], the [[Prime Minister of South Africa|South African Prime Minister]] who was a principal ideological force behind Apartheid doctrine.<ref name="Traitor"/>
The book became a best-seller, was translated into 11 languages<ref name=Vries> {{Citation| last = de Vries| first = Fred | title = The Fred de Vries Interviews - From Abdullah to Zille| publisher = Wits University Press| year = 2008| pages = 325| isbn = 978-1-86814-469-3}}</ref> and was still in print 14 years later. It has been called brilliant.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A16237-2004May10_5.html |title=White Fright |publisher=The Washington Post |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=22 October 2016 }}</ref>
